{
  "doc_id": "10497",
  "text": "The fact that changes in QRS morphology are accompanied by T-wave changes 11 referred to as cardiac memory 10 is well established. [CITATION_1] 13 The new findings are as follows: (1) One third of patients develop a change in QRS morphology at the time of AVB; (2) Such patients have greater QT prolongation and are at high risk of developing TdP; and (3) QRS morphology alterations also involving a change in QRS axis are associated with even greater QT prolongation. These observations demonstrate that cardiac memory affects QT prolongation during AVB.",
